AS REPORTED TO THE DEPARTMENT BY TELEPHONE ON JULY 2, 1993, A RELEASE OF HAZARDOUS WASTE FROM A MILL SERVICE TANK TRUCK ENROUTE TO THE YUKON PLANT OCCURRED AT APPROXIMATELY 3:00 PM ON THAT DATE.  THE WASTE INVOLVED WAS A SPENT PICKLE LIQUOR (HAZARDOUS WASTE NO K062) FROM THE ALLENPORT PLANT OF WHEELING-PITTSBURGH STEEL CORPORATION BEING TRANSPORTED UNDER MANIFEST NO PAE0243865 (COPY ATTACHED).  APPROXIMATELY 1 QUART (2.6 POUNDS) OF WASTE WAS INVOLVED IN THE RELEASE, RESULTING IN AN INTERNITTEN STAIN ON THE SURFACE OF SR 3059 AND SR 3061 FROM A POINT APPROXIMATEY 800 FEET SOUTH OF THE INTERSECTION OF THESE TWO ROADS TO THE PLANT. OUR INVESTIGATION OF THE INCIDENT INDICATED THAT THE RELEASE OCCURED FROM THE TANKER DISCHARGE ASSEMBLY.  BOTH THE MANUALLY-OPERATED AND AIR-OPERATED VALVES WERE FOUND TO BE SLIGHTELY A JAR AND THE THREADED JOINT THAT HOLDS THE CAP ONTO THE OUTLET END OF THE PIPE WAS LOOSE.  THE RELEASE WAS APPARENTLY TRIGGERED WHEN THE VEHICLE MOMENTARILY LEFT THE ROAD SURFACE ALONG SR 3061 NEAR WHERE THE RELEASE BEGAN.  NO EVIDENCE OF ANY STAINING ON THE ROAD SURFACE WAS EVIDENT SOUTH OF THAT LOCATION.  FURTHER, THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE INDICATED THAT AN INSPECTION OF THE ASSEMBLY PERFORMED ONLY MINUTES BEFORE THE RELEASE REVEALED NOTHING AWRY.  IN RESPONSE TO THE RELEASE, A STREET SWEEPER WAS CALLED TO THE SCENE AND ROAD SURFACE WET-VACUUMED ON JULY 2, 1993.  THERE IS NO EVIDENCE TO SUGGEST THAT ANY OF THE RELEASED WASTE OR THE WATER USED IN THE CLEANING PROCESS LEFT THE ROAD SURFACE.  ALL OF THE MATERIAL CLEANED FROM THE ROAD SURFACE WAS DELIVERED TO THE YUKON PLANT, TREATED AND DISPOSED.  IT IS OUR OPINION THAT NO ACTUAL OR POTENTIAL HARM TO THE ENVIRONMENT OR TO THE PUBLIC HEALTH, SAFETY OR WELFARE RESULTED FROM THE RELEASE.  CLOSE INSPECTION OF THE DISCHARGE ASSEMBLY ON THE VEHICLE REVEALED BOTH DISCHARGE VALVES TO BE IN EXCELLENT CONDITION AND FULLY CAPABLE OF CONTAINING THE WASTE.  IN ADDITION, THE CAP, AFTER TIGHTENING, WAS FOUND TO BE FULLY FUNCTIONAL.  WE DO NOT BELIEVE THAT ANY EQUIPMENT MODIFICATIONS ARE WARRANTED AT THIS TIME.  HOWEVER, THE IN-TRANSIT INSPECTION REQUIREMENTS OF THE TRANSPORTER CONTINGENCY PLAN HAVE BEEN REVISED TO INCLUDE AN INSPECTION OF ALL CLOSURE DEVICES ON THE WASTE TRANSPORT VEHICLES TO CONFIRM THAT THEY ARE SECURE.  ALL DRIVERS WILL RECEIVE TRAINING CONCERNING THIS ADDITIONAL INSPECTION REQUIREMENT. IF YOU HAVE ANY QUESTIONS CONCERNING THIS INCIDENT, PLEASE CONTACT ME.

THE CAR WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING A VAPOR FROM THE GUAGE DEVICE PACKING GLAND NUT, UPON IT'S ARRIVAL IN TUCSON, AZ. AFTER BEING PICKED UP AT BENSON, AZ. IT LEAK WAS A NOTICABLE HISS, BUT A VOPR ONLY.  THE WIND WAS FROM THE SOUTHWEST AND SUFFICENT THAT GROUND LEVEL SMELLING OF THE PORODUCT WAS DIFFICULT.  THE GUAGE ROD WAS LOOSENED, AND RAISED TO THE TOP IN ORDER TO BACK-SEAT THE ROD BASE AND REDUCE THE LEAK.  THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS THEN BQACKED OUT ALL THE WAY AND SEVERAL WRAPS AROUND THE ROD WITH TEFLON ROPE PACKING WERE PLACED IN THE PACKING GLAND.   THIS SECURED THE LEAK WHEN THE PACKING GLAND NUT WAS REINSTALLED.  THE FINAL INSTALLATION OF THE PACKING GLAND NUT HAD TO BE DONE WITH  A CROW'S FOOT WRENCH, AS THE INTEGRATED WRENCH FOR THE PACKING GLAND NUT HAD BEEN BROKEN OFF.  IT WAS ALSO NOTED THAT THE UPPER NUT ON THE GUAGE DEVICE HOUSING WAS "CROSS-THREADED" INTO THE HOUSING.  THUS, FORCING THE ROD TO BE SLIGHTLY OFF CENTER IN THE PACKING GLAND.  THIS MADE IT ALMOST IMPOSSIBLE TO TOTALLY SECURE THE PACKING GLAND AGAINST SEEPAGE.  AFTER SECUREMENT, THE CAR WAS SENT TO IT'S HOME SHOP TO HAVE THE GUAGE DEVICE REPAIRED OR REPLACED.

A VACUUM TRAILER WAS DISPATCHED TO WILEY ORGANIC, INC. LOCATED AT 1245 SOUTH 6TH STREET IN COSHOCTON, OH TO PICK-UP A LOAD OF METHANOL AND ETHYL ACETATE SCHEDULED TO BE DISPOSED OF AT SPRING GROVE RESOURCE RECOVERY, INC.  LOCATED AT 4879 SPRING GROVE AVENUE IN CINCINNATI, OH.  UPON COMPLETION O THE LOADING PROCEDURES, THE VEHICLE OPERATOR INITIATED STEPS REQUIRED TO DRAIN THE REMAINING PRODUCT FROM THE TRANSFER HOSES.  UNDER NORMAL CONDITIONS, THE VEHICLE OPERATOR USES THE VACUUM CAPABILITIES OF THE VEHICLE TO PULL THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE TRANSFER HOSE INTO THE TANK.  IN THIS SITUATION, HOWEVER, THE VACUUM FAILED AND APPROXIMATLEY 5-10 GALLONS OF PRODUCT DRAINED FROM THE TRANSFER HOSE ONTO THE GROUND. IT WAS DISCOVERED THAT THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THIS VEHICLE FAILED TO COMPLETELY SEAL THEREBY RELEASING ADDITIONAL MATERIAL INTO THE TRANSFER HOSE AND REDUCING THE VACUUM PRESSURE. THE DRIVER IMMEDIATELY HALTED ALL OPERATIONS, SECURED THE EXTERNAL VALVE AND NOTIFIED THE PROPERTY OWNER AND HIS HOME DISPATCHER.  THE DRIVER'S DISPATCHER, IN TURN, DISPATCHED A RESPONSE CREW TO THE SCENE TO CLEAN-UP THE PRODUCT THAT WAS RELEASED AND TO TRANSFER THE CONTENTS OF THE TANK INTO ANOTHER VEHICLE.  BOTH OPERATIONS WERE CONDUCTED WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT AND ALL SPILL DEBRIS WAS COLLECTED IN 55 GALLON DRUMS AND SENT FOR DISPOSAL AT A FULLY LICENSED WASTE MANAGEMENT FACILITY.  IN ORDER TO PREVENT A RECURRENCE OF THIS SITUATION, ALL VEHICLE OPERATORS WILL CONTINUE TO CONDUCT PROPER PRE AND POST TRIP INSPECTIONS OF THEIR VEHICLES.  IN ADDITION, THE INTERNAL VALVE ON THE VEHICLE INVOLVED IN THIS INCIDENT HAS BEEN REPAIRED.

THE SPEEDI DRY WAS PUT IN A PAIL AND MANIFESTED AS WASTE TRICHLOROETHYLENE.  THE PAIL WAS PUT ON ANOTHER LES (NORTH EAST) TRUCK WHO WAS AT RYDER FOR REPAIRS AND IT WAS TRANSPORTED BACK TO OUR 300 CANAL STREET LAWRENCE MA FACILITY.  TO PREVENT FURTHER SPILLS SUCH AS THESE, OUR DRIVER WILL BE TRAINED ON PROPER SAFETY PROCEDURES FOR DISCONNECTING THE HOSES.

column168: THE DRIVER WAS TRAVELING WEST ON OK 33 AND HAD JUST CROSSED OVER THE CIMARRON RIVER BRIDGE, ONE MILE EAST OF COYLE, OK.  UPON EXITING THE BRIDGE HEADED WEST, THERE IS A S CURVE. THE CONTAMINATED SAND WAS PICKED UP AND TRANSPORTED TO AN AUTHORIZED LANDFILL AT STILLWATER, OK.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY AT THE CUSTOMER'S.  HE CONNECTED THE PRODUCT HOSE AND PROCEEDED TO TRANSFER THE MATERIAL TO STORAGE.  AFTER UNLOADING FOR SOME TIME HE WAS ADVISED TO SHUT DOWN.  IT WAS FOUND THAT THE RECEIVER HAD LEFT A BLEED VALVE OPEN AND PRODUCT WAS ESCAPING INTO THEIR SUMP.  THE RECEIVER CLOSED THE BLEED VALVE AND OUR DRIVER COMPLETED HIS DELIVERY.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS REMOVED FROM THE SUMP BY THE CUSTOMER.

OUR DRIVER WAS CLEARED FOR DELIVERY.  SHE CONNECTED THE PRODUCT HOSE AND AIR SUPPLIED BY THE CONSIGNEE.  AS SHE OPENED THE UNLOADING VALVE PRODUCT SPRAYED FROM THE END OF THE HOSE.  PRODCUT WENT UP UNDER HER FACE SHIELD AND SHE RECEIVED A BURN TO THE SIDE OF HER NECK.  A CUSTOMER EMPLOYEE THEN SHUT OFF THE FLOW AND IN THE PROCESS ALSO RECEIVED A MINOR BURN.  THE FAILURE APPEARS TO HAVE BEEN DUE TO A COMBINATION OF DEFECTIVE GASKET AND EXCESS PRESSURE.

AFTER DRIVER GOT OK TO UNLOAD SIGNED HE WAS PUMPING PRODUCT INTO STORAGE TANK LOCATED INSIDE OF BUILDING. UNLOADER CAME OUT AND TOLD DRIVER TO SHUT DOWN.  TANK WAS FULL AND STARTED TO OVERFLOW THROUGH VENT.  CONSIGNEE NEUTRALIZED PRODUCT AND CLEANED UP AREA.  BALANCE OF PRODUCT WAS DRUMMED OFF.

BILL HANSELMAN OF OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CORP. CALLED MONTANA SULPHUR & CHEMICAL CO. APPROXIMATELY 2:15 PM MST 7/16/93 AND REPORTED TO MONTANA SULPHUR & CHEMICAL CO. THAT THEY HAD A SMALL H2S LEAK.  I WAS INFORMED OF THE LEAK AND RETURNED HIS CALL.  I WAS TOLD BY FRED OF OCCIDENTAL CHEMCIAL CO THAT THERE WAS NO RUSH TO REPAIR THE LEAK AS IT WAS APPROX. 1 PM.  I MADE ARRANGEMENTS FOR KLAY WAGNER & MYSELF TO FLY TO ASHTABULA, OHIO TO REPAIR THE LEAK.  WE ARRIVED AT ASHTABULA AT 11 PM 7/23/93.  KLAY AND I WENT OCCIDENTAL CHEMICAL CO. AROUND 8:00 AM 7/24/93.  WE COULD NOT DETECT ANDY PPM OF H2S AND GROUND LEVEL.  WE THEN WENT ON TOP OF THE TANK CAR AND STILL COULD NOT DETECT ANY LEAK FROM 1 FOOT AWAY.  WALT MILLER HAD LOCATED AND MARKED THE LEAK BEFORE WE GOT THERE.  WE THEN USED OUR DETECTOR 1 INCH AWAY AND GOT 6-10 PPM.  KLAY THEN USED OUR TORQUE WRENCH AND TORQUED THE BOLTS AROUND THE LEAK.  TORQUE WAS OK.  WE THEN RETORQUED AND CHECKED AND FOUND WE STILL HAD A SMALL LEAK, 2 PPM, SO WE RETORQUED THE BOLTS.  WE THEN LEFT THE PLANT AND RETURNED FIVE HOURS LATER.  WE FOUND THE CAR TO BE SAFE AND NOT A HAZARD.  WE THEN RETURNED TO BILLINGS ON 7/25/93 AM.  THERE WASNOT DANGER OR INJURY TO THE PUBLIC OR THE ENVIRONMENT AS A RESULT OF THIS SEEPAGE INCIDENT.

column58: Auxiliary Valve; Bottom Outlet Valve; Piping or Fittings
column168: SOU 995122 WAS NOTED BY CARRIER EMPLOYEE TO BE LEAKING FROM BOTTOM OUTLET CAP.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SPILL WAS CONTAINED IN BALLAST.  ALL STATE AND LOCAL SAFETY AND ENVIRONMENTAL AGENCIES WERE NOTIFIED.  BOTTOM OUTLET CAP WAS TIGHTENED TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKS.

SOU 995001 WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING BY CARRIER EMPLOYEE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED, VENDER NOTIFIED, AND BUCKETS WERE PLACED BENEATH CAR TO CATCH FUEL. APPROXIMATELY 5-6 GALLONS HAD LEAKED ON GROUND BEFORE THE BUCKETS WERE USED, BUT THE FUEL WAS ABSORBED INTO THE BALLAST AND GROUND.  THE CAUSE OF THE LEAK WAS OVERFILLING BY THE VENDOR WHO FILLED THE TANK FOR STORAGE. THE VENDOR AND EMPOLYEES FROM OUR MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT REMOVED ABOUT 200 GALLONS OF FUEL FROM CAR TO PREVENT ANY FURTHER LEAKS.  THIS CAR IS USED PRIMARILY FOR FUEL STORAGE.

DBCX 237 WAS NOTED TO BE EMITTING VAPORS BY A CARRIER EMPLOYEE.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND AAR CHIEF INSPECTOR WAS NOTIFIED.  AAR INSPECTOR FOUND THE CAUSE OF THE VAPOR RELEASE TO BE A MISSING "O" RING FROM THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  HE DID NOT HAVE THE CORRECT PART WITH HIM.  SHIPPER SENT OUTSIDE CONTRACTOR TO REPLACE MISSING "O" RING.  CONTRACTOR AND AAR INSPECTOR CLEANED OUTSIDE OF CAR TO REDUCE ODOR PRIOR TO OK'ING THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT.

ECUX 361019 WAS NOTED TO BE LEAKING BY CARRIER EMPLOYEE.  CAR WAS ISOALTED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  THE SHIPPER SAID THE LEAK WAS DUE THE BUILD UP OF PRESSURE INSIDE THE TANK DUE TO EXTREME HEAT.  THE CAR WAS RELEIVED OF THE PRESSURE THROUGH THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE LEAK WAS FOUND TO BE COMING FROM THE LIQUID LINE DUE T DEFECTIVE VALVE PLUG.  AFTER THE PRESSURE WAS RELIEVED, THE LEAKING STOPPED AND CAR WAS OK'ED FOR MOVEMENT.  SHIPPER REPRESENTATIVE REPLACED DEFECTIVE VALVE PLUG.
GATX 13508 WAS NOTED TO BE WET FROM PRODUCT.  CAR WAS ISOLATED AND SHIPPER NOTIFIED.  LEAK WAS DUE TO A DEFECTIVE MANWAY GASKET.  SHIPPER SENT SOMEONE TO REPLACE GASKET.  CAR WAS OK'ED FOR MOVEMENT.

PACKAGE WAS FOUND LEAKING IN THE PRIMARY, AND THE BOTTOM OF THE PACKAGE WAS DAMP.  THE PACKAGE WAS PROPERLY MARKED AND LABELED AS A HAZARD.  UPON OPENING THE PACKAGE WE FOUND THAT THE CAP ON THE PLASTIC JUG HAD POPPED OFF CAUSING ABOUT 5 OZ OF 4 LITERS TO LEAK OUT.  THE PACKAGE IS BEING HELD AT GRADE LANE HUB FOR FAA INSPECTION.
THE PUMP PACKING NUT WAS DEFECTIVE.  PUMP LEAKING.

WASTE DRUMS IN THE WAREHOUSE WERE BEING LOADED INTO A TRAILER  FOR SHIPMENT TO A TSDF. THE DOUBLE DRUM CLAMP ATTACHMENT WAS ON THE SHIPMENT TO A TSDF.  THE DOUBLE DRUM CLAMP ATTACHEMENT WAS ON THE FORKLIFT, AND BEING USED TO TRANSPORT THE 55 GALLON OPEN-TOP POLIES. THESE DRUMS CONTAINED SLUDGE. ONE POLY DRUM FELL FROM THE DRUM CLAMPS ONTO ITS SIDE AND THE TOP POPPED OFF. THE LIQUID CONTENTS SPILLED ONTO THE INSIDE OF THE TRAILER, THE DOCK PLATE AND RAN DOWN INTO A CONCRETE SUMP UNDER THE TRUCK. THE SUMP IS A CONCRETE STRUCTURE, IN GOOD CONDITION, DESIGNED TO HOLD SPILLS AS A SECONDARY CONTAINMENT AT THE DOCK. THE MATERIALS WERE WHOLLY CONTAINED IN THE SUMP. SPILLED MATERIALS WERE ABSORBED AND PLACED IN DOT CONTAINERS.  THE PROFILE SHOWED A PH OF 13, BUT THE DOT DESCRIPTION ON THE MANIFEST WAS "ENVIRONMENTALLY HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, LIQUID, N.O.S., 9 PG111 (D002, D007).  AFTER THE LIQUID MATERIAL SPILLED FROM THE DRUM, IT WAS HALF FULL WITH SOLIDS REMAINING IN THE BOTTOM. IT WAS HEAVY ENOUGH TO REQUIRE TWO PEOPLE TO PULL THE HALF FULL DRUM UPRIGHT. THE WASTE RESIDUE WHICH WAS NOT SPILLED IS BEING TESTED TO DETERMINE IF IT IS A HAZARDOUS WASTE (PH AND TCLP FOR CHROMIUM).

column168: I WAS GOING SOUTH ON US 169, IT JUST STOPPED RAINING.  I WAS ON NEW PAVEMENT WHEN RIGHT FRONT STEER TIRE WENT OFF ROAD. THE LAOD SHIFTED AND TRACTOR AND TRAILER WENT OVER ON ITS SIDE.  STATE POLIC WERE CALLED AND CAME OUT.  I TOLD THEM WHAT HAPPENED AND WHAT I HAD ON THE TRAILER. APPROXIMATELY ABOUT 100 GALLONS SPILLED OUT.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL WAS IN FORNT OF TOTE THAT THE LID CAME OFF OF.  IT ONLY SPREAD OUT ABOUT 5 FEET IN FRONT OF THE TOTE.  WHEN THE TRACTOR & TRAILER CAME TO A STOP, 4 OR 5 TOTES CAME THROUGH THE ROOF OF THE TRAILER, 1 TOTE FLEW ACROSS THE CREEK. IT LANDED ABOUT 10 TO 12 FEET FROM THE TRAILER.  NOTHING LEAKED OUT OF THAT TOTE.  THE OTHER 3 OR 4 TOTES LANDED ABOUT 3 FEET FROM THE TRAILER. THE REST OF THE TOTES STAYED INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE TOTE THAT LEAKED WAS STILL INSIDE THE TRAILER.  THE OPERATOR OF THE VEHICLE FELT ACCIDENT WAS DUE TO DESIGN AND NEW CONSTRUCTION OF HIGHWAY. THE WEATHER CONDITIONS CAUSED THE HIGHWAY TO BECOME SLICK AND NEW ASPHALT TO CONTAIN OIL.  NO VIOLATIONS WERE ISSUED.

CMGN TRAIN 701 WAS BACKING OUT OF OUR DURAND YARD TO MAKE A NORTH BOUND MOVEMENT ON OUR SAGINAW SUB.  CONDUCTOR ON REAR CAR OBSERVED CROSSOVER SWITCH OFF GTW WEST BOUND MAIN WAS PROPERLY LINED FOR HIS MOVE.  AT SOME POINT AFTER CHECK OF SWITCH WAS MADE, POWER SWITCH LINED IN FRONT OF REAR CAR CAUSING SAME TO RUN THROUGH SWITCH.  (IT SHOULD BE NOTED THAT DUE TO LIGHTNING FROM A STORM EARLIER THE CTC SYSTEM WAS NOT WORKING AND ALL SWITCHES HAD TO BE LINED BY HAND).  IT IS NOT KNOWN HOW THIS SWITCH LINED ITSELF AGAINST THIS MOVE.  WHEN CREW MADE A REVERSE MOVE, THE TRAILING SET OF TRUCKS ON DERAILED CAR TAILED DOWN CROSSOVE WHILE THE LEAD SET STAYED ON MAIN WITH THE REST OF THE TRAIN.  CAR MOVED UNTIL TANK BODY WAS PULLED OFF OF TRUCK CAUSING TRAIN TO GO INTO EMERGENCY.  CONDUCTOR WALKED BACK AND FOUND DERAILMENT AND MADE PROPER NOTIFICATIONS.

column168: DRIVER WAS LOADING A TANK TRAILER AT A TANK BATTERY CONSISTING OF TWO 210 BARREL TANKS.  BOTH TANKS LOAD OFF OF ONE MANIFOLD WITH EACH TANK HAVING IT'S OWN UNLOADING VALVE.  DRIVER WAS LOADING OIL FROM TANK #2 AND FAILED TO CLOSE THE VALVE ON TANK #1.  AS A RESULT, DRIVER OVERFILLED TRAILER. AN ESTIMATED 126 GALLONS OF OIL WAS ON THE GROUND.  COMPANY MACHINERY WAS BROUGHT IN TO CLEAN AND RESTORE AREA TO ITS ORIGINAL STATE.  LAND OWNER AGREED TO CLEAN UP METHODS USED AND HIGHLY APPROVED OF SITE ON THE COMPLETION.  BECAUSE OF EMPLOYEE NEGLIENCE, DRIVER WAS ASSESSED THREE DAYS OFF WITHOUT PAY AND ISSUED A LETTER OF FINAL WARNING IN REGARDS TO CONTINUED EMPLOYMENT.

column168: ON 07-10-93 RAM SUPERVISOR, CONNIE COOK, REPORTED A STRONG ODOR TOPSIDE OF THE AIRCRAFT PARKED AT GATE A-21.  UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, THE AREA WAS SECURED FROM PERSONNEL.  I, MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, NEAL VAN SAUN, RESPONDED. UPON ARRIVAL ON THE SCENE, I TOOK THE GAS DETECTION INSTRUMENT TOPSIDE OF THE AIRCRAFT AND OBSERVED THIS INSTRUMENT FOR ABNORMAL READINGS: NONE WERE OBSERVED.  THE OFF-LOAD OF THE UNIT LOAD DEVICES WAS STARTED.  THE SECOND UNIT LOAD WAS FOUND TO BE EMITTING THE ODOR.  UPON OPENING THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE, I FOUND INSIDE APPROXIMATELY 15 5-GALLON METAL RECEPTICLES.  THIS UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION.  DURING THE INVESTIGATION OF THE FIVE-GALLON METAL RECEPTICLES, I FOUND ONE THAT WAS LEAKING, THE CLOSURE WAS LOOSE.  THERE WAS NO MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED, AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THE SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED ONTO ITS DESTINATION.

column168: DEAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED BY GARY HUTNER, SUPERVISOR, YARD OPERATIONS, YERMO, CALIFORNIA, THAT TANK CAR GATX 43524 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR WHILE THE CAR WAS BEING HANDLED DURING NORMAL SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  THE CAR WAS SET TO THE CABOOSE TRACK AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION. MANAGER COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY AND INSPECTED THE CAR AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE FROM THE MANWAY NOZZLE AND COVER PLATE, AS EVIDENCED BY THE PRODUCT ON THE SIDES OF THE TANK CAR DIRECTLY BELOW THIS LOCATION.  UPON LOOSENING THE 8 MANWAY COVER PLATE SWING BOLTS AND RAISING THE COVER PLATE, IT WAS NOTED THAT THE MANWAY COVER HAD NO GASKET IN PLACE.  A GASKET WAS INSTALLED AND THE COVER PLATE SECURED.  THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO VARIFY PROPER SECUREMENT THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. NOTIFICATIONS WERE ONLY MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES, AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION.  DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE NOT MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA, OR SAN BERNARDINO COUNTY.

THE SAFETY VENT, A STANDARD MIDLAND BAFFLE, WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND THE RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE STAINLESS/TEFLON 100 POUND DISC.  THE GASKET MATERIAL ON THE AIR INLET BLIND FLANGE WAS WORN AND WAS REPLACED WITH A PIECE OF GORE-TEX MATERIAL WRAPPED AROUND THE PIPE OPENING AND COMPRESSED INTO PLACE BY TIGHTENING THE FLANGE.  THE CAR WAS MOVED SEVERAL TIMES TO ENSURE PROPER SECUREMENT, THEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT ONTO THE CONSIGNEE. column168: 1EAN COOPER, MANAGER, CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, WAS NOTIFIED THAT A TRAILER HAD BEEN RECEIVED AT THE LAS VEGAS TRAILER FACILITY, AND IT WAS LEAKING A LIQUID FROM THE NOSE AREA UNDERCARRIAGE.  MANAGER COOPER RESPONDED TO THE TRAILER RAMP AND LOCATED TRAILER CFKZ 630356 ON FLATCAR WC 36239 AS THE SECOND OR "B" UNIT.  THIS FLATCAR HAD MOVED REVERSED IN THE TRAIN CONSIST, WHICH HAD THE TRAILER DOORS FACING TOWARDS THE HEAD END OF THE TRAIN.  THIS POSITION ALSO HAD THIS TRAILER AHEAD OF THE "A" UNIT TRAILER, REAZ 231915.  THERE WERE TWO SUBSTANCES LEAKING FROM THE NOSE OF THE CFKZ 630356 TRAILER, ONE CLEAR, THE OTHER WHITE IN COLOR.  THE AN EPOXY TERRAZZO MATRIX (CORROSIVE) WAS DAMAGED AT THE LOWER ROLLING HOOP DRIPPING LIQUID FROM THE UNDERCARRIAGE OF THE "B" UNIT ALSO SPRAYED THE REAR AND LEFT SIDE OF THE "A" UNIT TRAILER.  INTERIOR INSPECTION DEVELOPED THE ENTIRE CONTENTS HAD SHIFTED TO THE REAR OF THE TRAILER, LEAVING A 3-4 FOOT VOID ACROSS THE NOSE.  DUE TO NO BLOCKING OR BRACING, THE RESULTING LOAD SHIFT CAUSED SEVERAL OPEN HEAD DRUMS OF EPOXY RESIN (NON HAZ) TO COMPRESS AND DISTORT, THUS RELEASING SOME OF THEIR CONTENTS.  ONE DRUM OF BY ADJACENT FREIGHT.  THE INWARD DENTING OF THE HOOP CAUSED THE METAL TO CRIMP, WHICH ALLOWED PRODUCT TO ESCAPE FROM THE DRUM.  CONTENTS OF THE TRAILER WERE TRANSLOADED BY EMPLOYEEES OF CONSOLIDATED FREIGHTWAYS.  THE DAMAGED CORROSIVE DRUM WAS PLACED INTO AN OVERPACK AND SECURED.  THE RESIN WAS SOLIDIFIED AND REMOVED AND THE TRAILER CLEANED OF THE RESIDUE.

THIS WAS A FIBERBOARD BOX THAT WAS PROPERLY MARKED, LABELED AND PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT TO IDENTIFY THE CONTENTS. column168: ON JULY 7, 1993 AT APPROXIMATELY 0243 HOURS, SORT LEAD 44, (FLORENCE ELLINGER) REPORTED SHIPMENT LEAKING AT BUILDING C, TRUCK DOCK EXCEPTION AREA OF OUR SORT FACILITY. NO EMPLOYEES WERE IN CONTACT WITH LEAKING SHIPMENT. LEAKING SUBSTANCE APPEARED TO BE INK. SHIPMENT WAS BAGGED AND TAKEN TO OUR HAZMAT SORT AREA FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION. ON JULY 14, 1993 SHIPMENT WAS OPENE  FOR COMPLETE INVESTIGATION TO THE CONTENTS. FOUND WAS A JET MARK PRINTER, PRINTER WAS OPENED, FOUND WERE TWO 500ML BOTTLES. ONE BOTTLE CONTAINED L-219 BLACK INK AND THE SECOND BOTTLE CONTAINED L-9219 MAKE-UP SOLUTION. THE L-219 BLACK INK APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE HOLE THAT WAS CUT IN THE BOTTOM OF THE PLASTIC BOTTLE. ALL CONTENTS WERE LOST. THE SECOND BOTTLE CONTAINED APPROXIMATELY 40ML OF THE L-9219 MAKE-UP SOLUTION. A M.S.D.S. WAS REQUESTED AND RECEIVED FROM THE SHIPPER. THE L-219 BLACK INK HAS A D.O.T. CLASSIFICATION OF FLAMMABLE LIQUID UN1193. THE L-9219 MAKE-UP SOLUTION CONTAINED METHYL ETHYL KETONE, FLAMMABLE LIQUID UN1193. THIS SHIPMENT CONSISTED OF TWO BOXES OF WHICH ONLY ONE LEAKED. THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO IDENTIFY THAT THESE SHIPMENTS WERE HAZARDOUS. BOXES WERE NOT SPECIFICATION BOXES. NO SHIPPER'S DECLARATION OF DANGEROUS GOODS WERE AFFIXED TO THE BOXES. THIS SHIPMENT WILL BE KEPT UNDER LOCK AND KEY UNTIL RELEASED BY THE FAA.

ON 07-13-93 HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SORT LEAD, LORI NEWMAN REPORTED A UNIT LOAD DEVICE THAT WAS EMITTING AN ODOR, AT THE HAZ MAT SORT.  MICHAEL A. FRYE, HAZARDOUS COORDINATOR AND HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, NEAL VAN SAUN RESPONED TO THE HAZMAT SORT.  UPON ARRIVAL AT THE HAZ MAT SORT THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE WAS IN A SECURED AREA.  SPECIALIST VAN SAUN OPENED THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AND FOUND THE SHIPMENT THAT WAS EMMITING THE ODOR.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING.  INSIDE THE FIBERBOARD BOX WERE 7 PIECES.  THERE WERE 4, ONE GALLON EACH ("CLEAR DISPERSANT"), THREE WERE "MULTI--PURPOSE CLEANER".  THE LEAK OCCURRED FROM THE FIBERBOARD BOX BEING LOADED ON ITS SIDE IN THE UNIT LOAD DEVICE AND FROM NOT HAVING A POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  ON THE OUTSIDE OF THE FIBERBOARD BOX WAS THE FOLLOWING:  "INNER PACKAGES COMPLY WITH PRESCRIBED SPECIFICATIONS."  THERE WERE NO MARKINGS OR LABELS TO IDENTIFY THE HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CONTAINED WITHIN.  PROPER CERTIFICATION DID ACCOMPANY THIS SHIPMENT.  THIS SHIPMENT WAS PLACED INTO A SALVAGE DRUM AND FORWARDED TO ITS DESTINATION.

ON 7-10-93 SORT SUPERVISOR, ANDY HOLMES REPORTED A SHIPMENT THAT WAS LEAKING AND EMITTING A STRONG ODOR, IN THE MAIN SORT.  I, MICHAEL FRYE, HAZARDOUS MATERIALS COORIDNATOR A HAZARDOUS MATERIALS SPECIALIST, NEAL VAN SAUN RESPONDED TO THE SCENE.  UPON ARRIVAL WE OBSERVED THE LEAKING SHIPMENT.  SPECIALIST VAN SAUN DONNED AN ORGANIC VAPOR CARTRIDGE RESPIRATOR TO INVESTIGATE THE INNER CONTENTS OF THE LEAKING FIBERBOARD BOX. INSIDE THE BOX WERE SEVERAL DIFFERENT TYPES OF RECEPTICLES.  ONE WAS A GLASS RECEPTICLE THAT CONTAINED "DEHYDRATED ALCOHOL-ETHYL ALCOHOL 200 PROOF".THIS SHIPMENT WAS THEN TAKEN TO THE HAZ MAT SORT FOR FURTHER INVESTIGATION I , MICHAEL FRYE HELD THIS SHIPMENT AND REQUESTED A MATERIAL SAFETY DATA SHEET FOR THE REMAINING COMMODITIES IN THE FIBERBOARD BOX. THE ALCOHOL WAS FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES, WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURE.  THESE BOTH LEAKED.  THERE WERE TWO, HALF PINT METAL RECEPTICLES WITH FRICTION TYPE CLOSURES, WITH NO POSITIVE MEANS TO SECURE THE CLOSURES.  THESE DID NOT LEAK, ALSO THIS FIBERBOARD BOX CONTAINED SOME OTHER MISC. ITEMS.  ONCE THE M.S.D.S. WERE OBTAINED IT WAS FOUND THAT THE TWO, ONE GALLON METAL RECEPTICLES WERE FLAMMABLE LIQUIDS.  NO MARKINGS, LABELS OR PROPER CERTIFICATION ACCOMPANIED THIS SHIPMENT TO INDICATE THAT ITS CONTENTS WERE REGULATED AS HAZARDOUS MATERIALS.  THIS SHIPMENT IS AT THE HAZ MAT SORT, IN THE SECURITY CAGE, PENDING FAA INVESTIGATION.

THE LOAD WAS BILLED AS FREIGHT OF ALL KINDS AND NO PLACARDS WERE DISPLAYED ON THE TRAILER.  UPRR CTS MANAGER ARLA ROQUET RESPONDED.  OVERNIGHT TRANSPORTATION CONTACTED AND CHECKED THE MANIFEST WHICH SHOWED 2 55 GALLON DRUMS OF CORROSIVE WERE JUST INSIDE THE DOORS   WHEN INSPECTED, BOTH DRUMS HAD THE PAINT EATEN OFF THE LOWER PORTIONS.  THE RIB OF ONE DRUM HAD RUBBED AGAINST THE OTHER DRUM RIB, CAUSING A LEAK.  THIS WAS IN THE LOWER THIRD OF THE DRUM.  JERRY WILLIAMS, OPERATIONS MANAGER, OVERNIGHT TRANSPORTATION, 2300 TIME ST., IRVING, TX 75061, AUTHORIZED EMTECH ENVIRONMENTAL SERVICES FOR THE CLEANUP.  THE DRUM WERE PLACED IN STEEL OVERPACKS WITH ABSORBENT.  THE FLOOR WAS NEUTRALIZED AND CLEANED, AS WAS ANY CONTAMINATED PACKAGING.  THE TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO AIR OUT UNTIL SUNRISE, AT WHICH TIME IT WAS SEALED AND RELEASED.  SEAL #1453464 ORIGINALLY SECURED THE TRAILER AND WAS REMOVED FOR CLEANUP.  SEAL #UP B 203096 SECURED THE TRAILER WHEN RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.

THE DRIVER THEN TRANSPORTED THE LOAD WITHOUT FURTHER INCIDENT TO IT'S DESTINATION IN CANTON, OHIO.  THE DRIVER WAS SITED FOR HAVING AN UNSECURE LOAD.

column168: HOLTRRACHEM TRAILER #53 (DEDICATED TO HYDROGEN PEROXIDE SERVICE) LEFT LOADING TERMINAL (9) AND WAS PROCEEDING EAST ON NC 74, APPROZIMATELY 6 MILES TO INTERSECTION OF NC 200 IN MONROE, NC LOADED WITH PRODUCT.  AFTER STOPPING FOR LIGHT, DRIVER, DONI-RAYE KENDRICK, PROCEEDED AHEAD AND TROUGH REAR VIEW MIRROR NOTICED LIQUID ON THE GROUND.  HE PULLED TO THE SIDE OF THE ROAD TO CHECK VALVES ETC AND FOUND THE TOP RUPTURE DISK HAD FRACTURED. FOLLOWING HOLTRACHEM'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURE HE CALLED THE NATICK, MA MAIN OFFICE AND SPOKE TO JOHN CHAMBERLAIN.  (BOTH WERE CONCERNED ABOUT SPILLAGE ALONG THE ROUTE CAUSING GRASS FIRES).  JOHN INSTRUCTED THE DRIVER TO RETURN ALONG THE ROUTE OBSERVING FOR FURTHER SPILLAGE AND TO CALL UNION COUNT EMERGENCY MANAGEMENT TO REPORT AS SOON AS HE ARRIVED. JOHN THEN CALLED JANET TUCKER, UNION COUNTY MANAGEMENT, TO REPORT THE KNOWN SPILL AND ADVISE OF DRIVER'S WHEREABOUTS, AS WELL AS PROPER RESPOONSE-WATER ONLY-DILUTE WITH WATER.  DRIVER REPORTED NO FURTHER SPILLAGE ALONG THE ROUTE AND PROCEEDED TO RINSE EQUIPMENT AND CHANGE RUPTURE DISK.  HE THEN RETURNED TO THE SENCE TO LEND ADVISE/ASSISTANCE TO FIRE MARSHALL LT. RON FOWLER.  WATER WAS USED TO DILUTE THE SPILL AND RINSE THE ROADWAY.  TRAFFIC WAS MOVING DURING THE CLEAN-UP, ROAD WAS NOT CLOSED, NO EVACUATION WAS NECESSARY.  ALL BACK TO NORMAL BY 11:00 AM AND THE DRIVER PROCEEDED TO HIS DESTINATION.

KELLY INSPECTED THE TANK CAR AND FOUND THAT THE TREE SWING BOLTS ON THE FILL PORT OPENING LOCATED ON THE MANWAY COVER WERE LOOSE AND THAT GASKET HAD SLIPPED OUT FROM UNDER THE FILL PORT COVER ALLOWING PRODUCT TO SPLASH OUT WHEN THE CART WAS MOVED. column168: ON JULY 22,1993 AT APPROXIMATELY 9:30 AM, A BENETO TANK LINES TRUCK CARRYING 10701 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE ROLLED OVER ON THE WEST SIDE OF HIGHWAY 59 JUST SOUTH OF MILEMARKER 6 WHILE TRAVELING SOUTHBOUND. BENETO TANK LINES IS OWNED BY STEVE BENETO WHO CAN BE REACHED AT THE ADDRESS AND PHONE NUMBER ABOVE.  THE ACCIDENT INVOLVED NO OTHER VEHICLES OR PEOPLE AND WAS CAUSED WHEN THE DRIVER, GLEN KIMBERLING, LOOKED AWAY FROM THE ROAD WHILE ADJUSTING HIS SEAT BELT.  THE PASSENGER SIDE WHEELS DRIFTED OFF THE HIGHWAY ONTO THE SOFT SHOULDER AND, WHILE THE DRIVER WAS ATTEMPTING TO DRIVE BACK UP ONTO THE HIGHWAY, ENTRENCHED THEMSELVES IN THE SOFT DIRT AND CAUSED THE TRUCK TO ROLL OVER.  THE VEHICLE WAS CAB-OVER TANKER TRUCK AND TRAILER, COMMONLY CALLED A SUPER TANKER.  DURING THE ROLLOVER THE TRUCK AND TRAILER SEPARATED AND THE TANK ON THE TRUCK WAS TORN FROM THE FRAME. THE TRAILER ENDED UP UPSIDE DOWN, THE TRUCK TANK RIGHTSIDE UP WITH A SLIGHT TEAR IN THE TANK WALL, AND THE TRUCK RIGHTSIDE UP WITH THE CABOVER COMPARTMENT LAYING WINDSHIELD DOWN ON THE GROUND.  THE DRIVER WAS SLIGHTLY INJURED (2 BROKEN RIBS, MINOR CUTS AND ABRASIONS), WAS TREATED AT DIXIE REGIONAL MEDICAL CENTER IN ST.GEORGE, AND HAS BEEN RELEASED.  7727 GALLONS OF UNLEADED GASOLINE WERE LOST INTO THE GROUND AND ARE IN THE PROCESS OF BEING RECOVERED.  THE REMAINING 2974 GALLONS WERE PUMPED OUT OF THE TRUCK TANK BY TRI-VALLEY PETROLEUM OF ST.GEORGE, UTAH AND WERE TAKEN TO THEIR BUSINESS FACILITY.  WITHIN MINUTES OF THE ACCIDENT THE COLORADO CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT WAS ON ONSITE.  SHORTLY THEREAFTER THE UTAH HIGHWAY PATROL ARRIVED INCLUDING TROOPER KENNETH BAYLES WHO WAS IN CHARGE AND ASSISTED BY TROOPER BRUCE FOX OF CEDAR CITY.  ULTIMATELY, ADDITIONAL ASSISTANCE WAS PROVIDED BY THE HURRICANE CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT, WASHINGTON CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT AND SHERIFF'S OFFICE, THE ARIZONA HIGHWAY PATROL, AND THE KANAB CITY FIRE DEPARTMENT. WORD OF THE ACCIDENT REACHED BENETO TANK LINES HEADQUARTERS IN SACRAMENTO, CALIFORNIA WITHIN AN HOUR AND WITHIN THE NEXT HOUR COMPANY PRESIDENT STEVE BENETO, HIS SAFETY DIRECTOR BOB MARCH, HIS VICE-PRESIDENT OF TRANSPORTATION PAUL SCHULTZ, AND HIS GENERAL MANAGER BILL MYERS HAD CHARTERED A JET AND WERE FLYING TO ST.GEORGE.  WHEN THEY ARRIVED ON SCENE, PUMPOUT OF THE PRODUCT REMAINING IN THE TRUCK TRAILER WAS INITIATED WITH THE ASSISTANCE OF TRI-VALLEY PETROLEUM.  BY EARLY AFTERNOON, AFTER AN ASSESSMENT OF THE SITUATION AND AN INABILITY TO  LOCATE A LOCAL UTAH HAZARDOUS WASTE HANDLING COMPANY, ENVIRONMENTAL TECHNOLOGIES OF LAS VEGAS, NEVADA WAS CONTRACTED BY BENETO TANK LINES TO HANDLE THE CLEANUP. ENVIROTECH ARRIVED ON SCENE AT APPROXIMATELY 8:00 PM.  USING A SKIPLOADER, BACKHOE, AND TRUCKS, 15 LOADS OF CONTAMINATED SOIL WERE TAKEN TO BEAR RIVER CONTRACTORS IN ST.GEORGE FOR TEMPORARY STORAGE.  BY NOON FRIDAY, BENETO HAD MADE ARRANGEMENTS WITH LOCAL LAND OWNER JACK EVES TO TEMPORARILY STORE THE SOIL ON HIS PROPERTY APPROXIMATELY 2500 YARDS OF SOIL HAD BEEN ANALYSIS.

ON O7/20/93 THIS AGENT WAS ON DUTY IN THE CORPUS CHRISTI AREA.  AGENT OVERHEARD THE DISPATCHER RELAYING TO THE KVAL20 THAT THE SINTON POLICE HAD REPORTED THAT ONE OF THE TANKCARS WAS LEAKING ON THE NORTHBOUND TRAIN. THE TRAIN CAME TO A STOP AT MP332, NORTH OF ODEM TEXAS.  I ADVISED THE KVAL20 THAT I WAS IN THE AREA AND WOULD ASSIST IN THE INSPECTION.  I ARRIVED AT 2110HRS AND FOUND TANKCAR CELX3218 WITH A VERY MINOR LEAK COMING FROM THE PROTECTIVE MANWAY.  A CLOSER INSPECTION, WITH PERSONAL PROTECTIVE  EQUIPMENT REVEALED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE THE VACCUM RELIEF VALVE.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT ON NORTH END OF THE OD TRACK.  2235 TRAIN MANAGEMENT WAS NOTIFIED.  2240-CHEMTREC, TRACY JACKSON WAS NOTIFIED. 2245-JEFF REEDER WAS NOTIFIED.  AT 2330 HRS JEFF BUIS OF CELANESE MADE CONTACT WITH THIS AGENT.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE LOAD WAS SECURED AND WOULD WAIT UNTIL THE MORNING.  0730 HRS, 07/21/93, MET WITH JEFF BUIS.  IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE VACUUM RELIEF VALVES'S O-RING WAS DAMAGED AND WOULD NEED TO BE REPLACED.  BUIS REPLACED THE ENTIRE VALVE.  THE CAR WAS RELEASED AT 0930 HRS TO DISPATCHER WAYNE GERTZ.

column168: DEAN C COOPER, MGR CTS, WAS NOTIFIED BY VALERIE PAPPAS, MGR. TRAIN OPERATIONS YERMO,CA., THAT TANK CAR UCLX 16055 WAS NOTED LEAKING FROM THE TOP PORTION OF THE CAR DURING NORMAL YARD SWITCHING OPERATIONS.  ONE SWITCHPERSON STANDING NEXT TO THE TANK CAR WAS SPLASHED WITH THE COMMODITY AS THE CAR WAS BEING MOVED.  THE CAR WAS LEFT IN YARD TRACK #13 AND ISOLATED PENDING INSPECTION.  MGR. COOPER DROVE TO THE YERMO YARD FACILITY, INSPECTED CAR, AND DEVELOPED THE SOURCE OF THE LEAK TO BE A BURST RUPTURE DISC IN THE SAFETY VENT.  THE SAFETY VENT WAS DISASSEMBLED, AND RUPTURE DISC REPLACED WITH A LIKE TYPE 100 POUND DISC.  THE SIGHT GLASS WAS ALSO BROKEN OUT WHEN THE RUPTURE DISC BURST, AND SINCE THIS WAS NOT A REPLACEMENT READILY AVAILABLE, THE CAR WAS PLACED INTO "BAD ORDER" STATIS AND MOVED ONTO THE CAR, THE CAR WAS REMOVED FROM HOLD STATIS AND MOVED ONTO THE CONSIGNEE FOR DELIVERY.  NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO CHEMTREC FOR REPORTING PURPOSES AND TO THE SHIPPER FOR CORRECTIVE ACTION. DUE TO THE MINIMAL AMOUNT OF PRODUCT SPILLED, NOTIFICATIONS WERE MADE TO THE STATE OF CALIFORNIA, OR SAN BERNADINO COUNTY.

column168: AT 1140HRS ON7-22-93 WHILE INSPECTING LOADED TANK CAR EDCX 6202 NOTED VAPOR BEING RELEASED FROM THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE AND HAD CAR SET-OOUT INTO AN ISOLATION TRACK.  A SECOND INSPSECTION OF CAR REVEALED THAT THE SAFETY RELIEF VALVE HAD RE-SET ITSELF AND WAS NO LONGER RELEASING VAPOR. AT 1330 HRS CONTACTED SHIPPER, EL DORADO CHEMICAL, AND SPOKE TO MR. GERALD MARTIN.  IT WAS AGREED THAT THE FOLLOWING MORNING, THE HEAD PRESSURE IN THE CAR WOULD BE REDUCED BY CONNECTING AN AIR LINE TO THE AIR INDUCTION VALVE, OPEN THE VALVE TO RELIEVE PRESSURE AND SCRUB THE VAPORS WITH A SODIUM BARREL TO WHICH THE AIR LINE WOULD BE RUN.  AT 0830HRS ON 7-23-93, THE AIR INDUCTION VALVE WAS OPENED AND CAR MONITORED.  AT 1300HRS CAR WAS COUPLED TO A SWITCH ENGINE AND MOVED TO DETERMINE IF THERE WERE ANY ADDITIONAL LEAKS AT 1500HRS CAR WAS RELEASED FOR SHIPMENT WITH NO EXCEPTIONS NOTED.  NOTIFICATIONS: 1700 HRS CHEMTREC, JOE DEBNAM #23363; 1620 HRS TRAIN MANAGEMENT; AND 1045 HRS ON 7-27-93, NEBRASKA DEPT. OF ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY, ED LOUIS, #012793 -EL-1045.  EL DORADO CHEMICAL RECORDS INDICATE CAR OUTAGE AT 8%. AS A RESULT OF THE HEAT AND TIME ENROUTE, MR.MARTIN WILL HAVE CARS LOADED WITH AN INCREASED OUTAGE OF 10-12% TO COMPENSATE.

ON O7/23/93 AT 1145 HOURS, ROBERT D. FORDEMWALT, SR SA-HM, WAS NOTIFIED BY DICK WILSON, YARDMASTER, NAMPA, ID THAT AN EMPLOYEE HAD BEEN SPLASHED WITH ACID AT THE GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL RECEIVING TRACK.  I RESPONDED TO THE SCENE AND JIM BEATTY, CONDUCTOR, YNA66 23, STATED THAT HE WAS NOT INJURIED AND THE ACID THAT SPLASHED ON HIM ONLY HIT HIS CLOTHING AND NOT ANY OF HIS SKIN AREA.  GARY BONNER, MTO, AND DON FRASHIER, CLAIMS OPERATIONS, WERE AT THE SCENE.  ALSO, MARK SUMMERS, CUSTOMER SERVICE, GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL, WAS AT THE SCENE.  THE LISTED TANK CAR WAS LEAKING FROM UNDER THE WEATHER CAP, WHICH IS THE COVER FOR THE FRANGIBLE DISC.  INSPECTION AND REPAIR WILL BE CONDUCTED BY GREAT WESTERN CHEMICAL, AS STATED BY MARK SUMMERS. THE TYPE OF SYSTEM GATC SIEVE, LOCATED IN THE WORKING PLATFORM TO THE LEFT OF THE MANWAY COVER.  TYPE OF DISC IS UNKNOWN, BECAUSE LISTED TANK CAR HAS NOT BEEN UNLOADED OR REPAIRED AS OF 08/12/93.

column62: Defective Component or Device; Water Damage
column168: REGIONAL MANAGER NOTED EVIDENCE OF PRODUCT ON BOTH SIDES OF CAR WHICH APPEARED TO HAVE LEAKED FROM THE DRAIN HOLES IN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING. UPON INSPECTION NOTED A GREENISH LIQUID SUBSTANCE ON THE MANWAY PRESSURE PLATE WITHIN THE PROTECTIVE HOUSING AND ALSO IN THE BASE OF SAFETY VALVE. NOTED SAMPLE VALVE WAS EQUIPPED WITH A BLIND FLANGE WHICH WAS COCKED HAVING 1/4 THE SPACE ON ONE SIDE AND ONE OF THE FOUR SECUREMENT BOLTS FINGER TIGHT, ONE THE NUT WAS ONLY STARTED ON THE BOLT, THE OTHER TWO WRENCH TIGHT.  CAR HAD 17 INCH OUTAGE AND WAS NOT OVERLOADED.  CONTACTED LARRY THOMPSON OF MILES INC AND REQUESTED ON SITE MEETING.  AT 1300 HOURS MR.THOMPSON, JOHN SHEAN AND PHIL PAGE MET AND DISCUSSED OPTIONS.  THEY ALSO FELT THE SAFETY VALVE HAD OPERATED SOMETIME DURING TRANSPORT AND ALLOWED A SLIGHT AMOUNT OF PRODUCT TO ESCAPE.  THE GREEN LIQUID WOULD HAVE RESULTED FROM THE REACTION OF THE MATERIAL ON THE PAINTED SURFACE.  THE MATERIAL ON THE SIDES OF THE CAR HAD DRIED AND WE COULD DETECT NO EVIDENCE THAT CAR WAS LEAKING AT THE TIME OF THIS INSPECTION.  THE CAR HELD ACCOUNT FLOOD WATERS. LARRY THOMPSON ADVISED THEY WOULD TAKE THE CAR INTO THEIR PLANT AS SOON AS THE FLOODING WOULD ALLOW.  JULY 29, 1993, CONTACTED KCS SUPT., STEVE DUPONT, WHO AGREED TO MAKE A SPECIAL MOVE TO GET THE SET TO MILES.  NO EVIDENCE OF ANY FURTHER LEAKAGE.  CAR WILL BE UNLOADED AND SENT TO SHOP FOR INSPECTION.

UPRR SWITCH PERSONNEL AT ADDIS, LOUISIANA NOTED A SMALL AMOUNT OF LIQUID DRIPPING FROM THE SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND ISOLATED WITH OUT INCIDENT AT ADDIS.  UPON NOTIFICATION, UPRR MANAGER OF TRAIN OPERATIONS, BOB LENZER, CONTACTED UPRR REGIONAL MANAGER-CHEMICAL TRANSPORTATION SAFETY, T.M. ROBINSON.  ROBINSON INSPECTED THE CAR AND FOUND THAT THE FRANGIBLE DISC, A 95-100 PSI, CDC, STAINLESS STEEL AND TEFLON DISC, HAD BURST.  THE DISC WAS INSTALLED IN A SAFETY VENT ASSEMBLY THAT WAS MOUNTED ON ITS OWN NOZZLE JUST OUTSIDE THE "WORKING PLATFORM" AREA OF THE CAR.  THE SAFETY VENT INCORPORATED A "MIDLAND BAFFLE". THE FAILED DISC WAS REPLACED WITH A NEW CDC DISC OF SIMILAR SPECIFICATIONS. THE CAR WAS SECURED AND RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  ROBINSON NOTIFIED MR.BILL GASSON OF CHEMTREC AND WAS SUBSEQUENTLY CONTACTED BY MR.HERMAN LABLANC OF GEORGIA GULF.

column168: ON JULY 15, AT APPROX 0850, WHILE LOADING FLT 52 I WAS PUTTING CARGO INTO THE AFT CARGO COMPARTMENT WHEN I NOTICED A BOX SMOKING AND MAKING A SIZZLING NOISE.  I QUICKLY BRUSHED THE BOX OFF THE BELT LOADER ONTO THE GROUND. WHEN THE SMOKING AND SIZZLING STOPPED I OPENED THE BOX AND FOUND A PACKAGE OF 3 STRIKE-ANYWHERE MATCHES.  THE CENTER BOX HAD IGNITED.  I MADE SURE THE CARGO BOX HAD NO MORE RESTRICTED ARTICLES IN IT AND SHIPPED IT WITHOUT THE MATCHES.  I THEN REPORTED THE INCIDENT TO STEVE CARLISLE, ALASKA AIRLINES GROUND OPERATIONS MANAGER.

column168: WHILE DRIVING FROM GENERATOR TO TSDF; DRIVER WAS ALERTED BY PASSING MOTORIST WHO SOUNDED THEIR HORN AND POINTED AT HE TRAILER.  THINKING THE UNIT HAD A TIRE PROBLEM, DRIVER PULLED ONTO SHOULDER AND EXAMINED THE VEHICLE DISCOVERING LIQUID LEAKING FROM TRAILER FLOOR.  DRIVER UTILIZED ON-BOARD CONTAINMENT ITEMS TO DIKE AND CONTIAN THE LIQUID LEAKING FROM THE VEHICLE.  DRIVER'S HELPER WENT TO TELEPHONE AND NOTIFIED THE ON-DUTY SPILL COORDINATOR WHO DISPATCHED CLEAN VENTURE'S OWN SPILL TEAM.  THE DISPATCHER ALSO NOTFIED THE TRANSPORTIAON MANAGER WHO NOTIFIED THE N.R.C. (CASE #118112), AND THE PA. DER. ON ARRIVAL, THE SPILL TEAM REMOVED DRUMS FROM THE REAR OF THE UNIT TO MAKE ROOM AROUND THE LEKAING DRUM. SAID DRUM WAS OVERPACKED AND THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS CLENED USING ABSORBENT MATERIALS. SPILL TEAM THEN CLEANED UP THE SPILLAGE UNDER THE UNIT, INCLUDING THE ABSORBENT/DIRT UTILIZED TO DIKE THE SPILL INTO A CLEAN DOT 17H DRUM. AFTER INSPECTION BY THE LOCAL FIRE DEPARTMENT; THE EXTRA DRUM WAS LABELED AND ADDED TO THE LOAD.  THE HAZARDOUS WASTE MANIFEST WAS UPDATED IN SECTION 19. TO SHOW THE ADDITIONAL DRUM OF MATERIAL.  THE SPILL WAS CONTAINED ON THE SHOULD AND DID NOT REACH THE GRASS/DIRT ALONG THE SHOULDER.

CONDUCTOR R. A. HAHN, III, WHILE COUPLING TRACK 20, ALLENTOWN YARD AT 1030 ON JULY 28TH, WAS SPLASHED ON THE ARM WITH PRODUCT FROM GCTX 413138. MR. HAHN WAS TRANSPORTED TO ST. LUKES HOSPITAL, BETHLEHEM, PA WHERE HE WAS TREATED FOR A "MINOR CHEMICAL BURN"  AND RELEASED TO RETURN TO WORK. CONRAIL CONTACTED CHEMTREC FOR ASSISTANCE.  PAUL BROSSMAN OF GENERAL CHEMICAL REQUESTED AND RECEIVED THE ASSISTANCE OF AAR, BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR A.W. RICHTER.  MR. RICHTER REPLACED A RUPTURED #100, BS & B DISK SULFURIC ACID FROM THE CAR AND RELEASED THE CAR FOR TRANSPORT.

GATX 10050 WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING FROM THE RUPTURE DISK AT 0525 ON JULY 22ND IN SELKIRK YARD.  THE GENERAL CAR FOREMAN REPLACED THE DISK BUT DID NOT BELIEVE THAT IT WAS PROPERLY SECURED.  THEREFORE, HE ASKED BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES INSPECTOR A.W. RICHTER TO GO ON ROUTINE INSPECTION TO EXAMINE THE CAR.  WHILE THE DISKS SECUREMENT FLANGE DID APPEAR TO BE BENT MR. RICHTER REPLACED THE DISK, SECURED THE FLANGE AND WASHED THE AFFECTED AREA OF THE CAR.  THE CAR WAS ALLOWED TO SIT AND BUILD-UP PRESSURE. REEXAMINATION IN MID-AFTERNOON REVEALED NO LEAKS AND THE CAR WAS APPROVED FOR TRANSPORT.

ADVISED BY CSX OPS CTR. THAT MECHANICAL DEPARTMENT PERSONNEL WERE INSPECTING CARS IN #7 TRACK TILFORD YARD AND NOTED A WETNESS AROUND THE DOME AND DETECTED A SLIGHT ODOR AROUND CAR GATX 2419. THE BUCKET FELL TO THE FLOOR AND LANDED UPSIDE DOWN.  THE UNLOADER PICKED IT UP TO PLACE IT RIGHT SIDE UP AND THE COVER CAME OFF; THE LIQUID INSIDE FLOWED INTO HIS BOOTS AND SPLATTERED ON HIS ARMS.  THE EMPLOYEE WAS TAKEN TO HAZARDOUS MATERIAL RECOVERY AREA AND WAS SHOWERED OFF AND IMMEDIATELY TAKEN TO DOCTOR'S INN.  AS A RESULT OF CONTACT, HE RECEIVED FIRST AND SECOND DEFRESS BURNS TO ARMS AND FEET.  THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL WAS CONTAINED AND DISPOSED OF PER PROCEDURE USING SOLUSORB.  DAMAGE INSPECTION REPORT #490209.  THE RECOMMENDATIONS FOR PACKING PER THE UPS GUIDE FOR SHIPPING HAZARDOUS MATERIALS CALL FOR FIBERBOUARD BOX, 200LBS BURSTING STRENGTH, USING CORRUGATED LINERS AND LOOSE FILL TO ABSORB LEAKAGE.  MAXIMUM SHIPPED SHOULD BE 4 GALLONS (IN 1 GALLON CONTAINERS).  PACKING REQUIREMENTS WERE MET.

column58: Basic Material; Closure (e.g., Cap, Top, or Plug)
column168: TUESDAY JULY 27, RECEIVED CALL FROM MEM HUB, AT 2:50AM. AN EMPTY ICN RADIOCHEMICALS BOX WAS DISCOVERED AT THE EAST REWRAP LOCATION IN THE HUB. IT IS NOT KNOWN WHO BROUGHT THE EMPTY BOX, THIS IS KNOWN WHERE THE EMPTY BOX WAS FOUND.  THE DOCUMENTATION IS STILL ON THE BOX, THIS INFORMATION IS RECORDED AND THE CORPORATION'S RADIATION CONSULTANT, DR ROY PARKER WAS CONTACTED. DR PARKER STATES THAT INSTRUMENTATION WILL BE OF LITTLE VALUE IN LOCATING THE SOURCE, AND RECOMMENDS I CONTACT ICN FOR A PHYSICAL DESCRIPTION OF THE INNER PACKAGING.  I SPOKE TO TONY DENICOLA, WHO PROVIDED ME WITH A DETAILED DESCRIPTION OF THE SOURCE.  THE INFORMATION IS RELAYED TO THE HUB TO ASSIST IN THE SEARCH FOR THE SOURCE. THE HUB IS SEARCHED THROUGHOUT THE DAY TUESDAY, AND EARLY WEDNESDAY WITHOUT SUCCESS. WEDNESDAY JULY 28, AT APPROX. 9:00AM, ALLEN GREWE (TENNESSEE DIVISION OF RADIOLOGICAL HEALTH), AN ASSOCIATE AND MYSELF GO TO THE HUB, PRIOR TO SORT START-UP, AND CHECK THE SORT AREAS, INCLUDING THE DESTINATION AREA FOR THE PACKAGE (CHICAGO). STILL, NO SOURCE CAN BE LOCATED.  THE ORIGIN STATION IN CALIF. IS CALLED, AND WE ATTEMPT TO CONFIRM THE FLIGHT NUMBER THE PACKAGE WAS TRANSPORTED TO MEM ON, AIRCRAFT TYPE, AND LOAD POSITION ON THE AIRCRAFT, IN ORDER TO CONFIRM LOAD IN A ULD, VS A BULK LOAD IN A BELLY COMPARTMENT.  THE PACKAGE IS BELIEVED TO HAVE TRAVELED TO MEM VIA LAX. THE SEARCH FOR THE SOURCE CONTINUES AT THE MEM HUB. BETWEEN 2:00 AND 4:00 PM, I SPEAK TO ICN'S RSO, DAVID KRUGER; BOB KAYLOR AND CHARLIE BRYANT, TN EMER. MGT. ACNCY.  THE 28TH PASSES WITHOUT LOCATING THE SOURCE. THURSDAY, JULY 29 SOURCE STILL MISSING. RECEIVE INQUIRIES FROM GREG SCARFO, NRC, WASHINGTON; DOUG COLLINS, NRC, ATLANTA.  SUMMARY OF ACTIVITIES TO DATE ARE RELAYED.  RECEIVE INFORMATION FROM ORIGIN STATION THAT EARLIER FLIGHT LEG WAS IN ERROR.  ON THE DAY SHIPMENT, ALL THE ICN PACKAGES WENT TO LONG BEACH (LGB), AND THEN DIRECT TO MEM. MEM HUB IS ASKED TO LOCATE CONTAINER/AIRCRAFT OFFLOAD RECORDS FOR THE 27TH, TO CONFIRM THE INPUT AT WHICH THE LGB FLIGHT WAS UNLOADED.  FRIDAY JULY  30 INPUT FOR THE LGB FLIGHT IS CONFIRMED AS THE NORTH EAST;ALSO, THE FLIGHT PAPERWORK IS RECEIVED FROM ORIGIN STATION AND RAMP, AND CONFIRMS THE LGB FLIGHT AS CORRECT, AS WELL AS THE LOAD LOCATION ON THE AIRCRAFT. WE NOW ARE QUITE CERTAIN THAT THE PACKAGE WAS IN A SEALED ULD AND THUS NOT DAMAGED IN TRANSIT TO THE INPUT ON THE RAMP, WE ARE ALSO CERTAIN THAT IT WAS INITIALLY UNLOADED AT THE NE INPUT.  THIS INFORMATION IS RELAYED TO THE HUB, BUT STILL THE SOURCE IS NOT LOCATED.  SATURDAY, JULY 31 AT APPROX 7:00 AM, I ARRIVED AT THE HUD, AND AFTER CONFIRMING NO MAINTAINCE ACTIVITIES ARE PLANNED, PROCEED TO CHECK THE NE SORT AREA AS WELL AS ALL THE BELT WHICH COULD ULTIMATELY FEED TO THE CHICAGO OUTBOUND FLIGHT. THIS SEARCH TAKES APPROX 2 HRS TO COMPLETE, AND STILL NO SOURCE IS LOCATED.

PASSENGER TRIED TO PLACE ACID IN ANTIFREEZE CONTAINER WHICH WAS PLACED INSIDE FINBERBOARD BOXS.  THE PASSENGER INDICATED THAT CERAMIC POTTERY AND BOOK WERE INSIDE THE BOXES.  ONE OF THE BOXES STARTED LEAKING AFTER IT HAD BEEN PLACED ON OUR BAGGAGE CART.  (THE CART HAD ALREADY BEEN TAKEN TO PLANE SIDE).  AS ONE OF OUR EMPLOYEES PICKED UP THE BOX TO LOAD, HE NOTICED STRONG FUMES AND REALIZED THE BOX CONTAINED A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CHEMICAL.  AS THE BOX WAS PLACED ON THE GROUND, THE BOTTOM GAVE WAY CAUSING SPILLAGE ON OUR FLIGHT LINE.  THE AIRPORT CITY OFFICIALS WERE NOTIFIED ALONG WITH THE HAZARDOUS MATERIAL CREW TO INSPECT AND PERFORM CLEANUP.

AT APPROXIMATELY 1910 HRS ON 7/10/93 ADDIS, LA MTO BOB LENZER NOTIFIED SPECIAL AGENT T.J. BOUDREAUX AND ADVISED THAT TANK CAR PPGX 3009 WHILE BEING SWITCHED, SPLASHED PRODUCT FROM THE TOP OF THE CAR AND SPRAYED SWITCHMAN BASILE SCALISE IN THE FACE AND ON HIS ARM.  SCALISE IMMEDIATELY FLUSHED THE AREAS OF HIS BODY THAT WERE AFFECTED AND DID NOT WANT TO REPORT AN INJURY OR GO TO THE HOSPITAL FOR OBSERVATION.  THE PRODUCT WAS FOUND TO BE SODIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION.  BOUDREAUX RESPONDED AND ARRIVED IN THE ADDIS, LA YARD AT 2125 HRS, ON 7/10/93 AND LOCATED TANK CAR PPGX ON TRACK #15.  AN INSPECTION WAS MADE AND IT WAS NOTED THAT THE PRODUCT WAS SPLASHING OUT DUE TO A DEFECTIVE MANWAY COVER GASKET.  AT 2330 HRS. BOUDREAUX CONTACTED PETER POLIZE OF DOW CHEMICAL CO. IN PLAQUEMINE, LA AND REQUESTED A COMPATIBLE GASKET TO APPLY TO THE MANWAY.

AT 0915 HRS. ON 071293 S/A T.J. BOUDREAUX WAS ADVISED THAT THERE WERE TWO (S) TANK CARS LEAKING IN THE AMA, LA. YARD. UPON ARRIVAL, MET WITH THE ST. CHARLES PARISH FIRE DEPT & LOUISIANA STATE POLICE. THE FIRE DEPT HAD SET UP A COMMAND POST APPROXIMATELY 1/2 MILE FROM THE TANK CARS. INFORMED BY STATE TROOPER THAT BOTH TANK CARS WERE LEAKING WITH AN OCCASIONAL ODOR ON THE NORTH EAST SIDE OF THE SCENE TOWARD A RESIDENTAL TRAILER PARK. THE PARK CARS WERE GENERAL PURPOSE CARS. TANK CAR UTLX 201146 WAS INSPECTED AND FOUND TO HAVE A LOOSE LIQUID VALVE, LIQUID VALVE CAP, AND AIR INDUCTION VALVE. ALL THREE WERE TIGHTENED. AT APPROXIMATELY 1030 HRS UNION CARBIDE RESPONDERS ARRIVED AND THEY WERE ADVISED OF THE SITUATION. A SLIGHT ODOR WAS STILL ESCAPING FROM THIS TANK CAR AND THE MANWAY GASKET WAS SUSPECTED. IT WAS DECIDED THAT THE TANK CARS WOULD BE MOVED TO UNION CARBIDE CHEM. PLANT IN TAFT, LA. CHEMTREC WAS NOT CONTACTED DUE TO THE FACT THAT UNION CARBIDE REPRESENTATIVES WERE ON THE SCENE AND THEY WOULD CONTACT AND ADVISE THE NORTH SEADRIFT, TX. PLANT PERSONNEL OF OUR FINDINGS. THE ST. CHARLES PARISH FIRE DEPARTMENT WERE ADVISED OF OUR DECISION AND DEPARTED THE SCENE.

JJ TRANSPORT INL MADE A DELIVERY TO LOEDER OIL ON 070693. THE DRIVER MAKING THE DELIVERY LEFT THE VALVE TO THE #2 FUEL OIL TANK OPEN. ON 070793 ANOTHER DRIVER MADE A DELIVERY TO LOEDER OIL. THE DRIVER OPENED THE VALVE TO TANK #3 WHICH IS THE PROPER TANK FOR HIS DELIVERY OF PREMIER DIESEL FUEL. THERE IS JUST ONE LINE THAT GOES TO BOTH THE #2 FUEL OIL AND THE PREMIER DIESEL TANKS. THE DRIVER STARTED PUMPING, BUT BECAUSE THE VALVE FOR THE #2 FUEL OIL TANK WAS LEFT OPEN FROM THE DELIVERY ON 070693. PRODUCT WAS THEN BEING PUMPED INTO BOTH TANKS. BECAUSE THE #2 FUEL OIL TANK WAS ALMOST FULL THERE WAS APPROXIMATELY 53 GALLONS OF PREMIER DIESEL FUEL SPILLED OUT OF THE TANK VENT. WISCONSIN DNR, LOCAL EMERGENCY GOVERNMENT AND GREAT WEST CASUALTY WERE CALLED. A SITE CLEAN-UP HAS BEEN PERFORMED. AWAITING RESULTS AND DIRECTION FROM WI DNR.
